A Docker registry is basically a storage + distribution system for container images. If you’re using Docker seriously, this is not optional—you either use someone else’s registry or run your own.

What it actually is

Think of it like GitHub, but for container images instead of code.

You push images to a registry
Others (or your servers) pull images from it
It stores different versions (tags) of images
The main one everyone uses
Docker Hub
Default public registry
Easy, but:
Rate limits (especially for anonymous pulls)
Not ideal for private enterprise use unless you pay
Other popular registries (and why they exist)
Cloud-managed registries
Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR)
Google Container Registry (GCR)
Azure Container Registry (ACR)

These exist because:

Better integration with their cloud platforms
Built-in IAM/security
Faster pulls inside their ecosystem
Self-hosted / private registries
Docker Registry
Barebones, minimal features
Harbor
Actually production-grade:
RBAC
Vulnerability scanning
Replication

If you're serious about infra, Harbor > plain Docker Registry.

Core concepts you need to understand
1. Image naming
<registry>/<namespace>/<image>:<tag>

Example:

docker.io/library/nginx:latest
2. Push / Pull flow

Pull

docker pull nginx

Push

docker tag myapp username/myapp:v1
docker push username/myapp:v1
3. Public vs Private images
Public → anyone can pull
Private → requires authentication
When you actually need your own registry

Be honest here—most beginners don’t.

You need one if:

You’re deploying apps in production
You want private images
You care about security/scanning
You want faster internal pulls
Common mistake (don’t do this)

People think:

“I’ll just build images locally and copy them to servers”

That’s amateur hour.

Proper flow:

Build image
Push to registry
Deploy from registry
Bottom line
A Docker registry is infrastructure, not a feature
If you skip it, your deployment pipeline is broken
Start with Docker Hub, move to ECR/GCR/ACR or Harbor when scaling

